<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 01-03-07 - Dealer Pre-Delivery/Quality Inspection (P&#38;D) Process for Models Equipped with
        International Air Suspension Codes 14673, 14693, 14694
    </stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi010307" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>01-03-07</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>December, 2001</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>SPRINGS</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Dealer Pre-Delivery/Quality Inspection (P&#38;D) Process for Models Equipped with International Air
                Suspension Codes 14673, 14693, 14694
            </subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <ucodegroup/>

                <ucode>14673</ucode>
                <ucode>14693</ucode>
                <ucode>14694</ucode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>During the truck Pre-Delivery/Quality Inspection (P&#38;D) process the International dealer is
                    responsible to verify that the air spring height is within specification limits and if necessary
                    make corrections to meet specification.
                </para>
                <para>When the air bag height cannot be brought into specification limits due to a problem with the
                    height control valve, the valve should be replaced by a qualified truck technician.
                </para>
                <randlist type="bullet">
                    <item>
                        <para>Torsional vibration will increase when the air spring height is out of specification
                            limits. Transmission failures determined to be caused by torsional vibration may not be
                            covered by warranty.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Chassis ride quality cannot be improved by modifying the height control valve linkage to
                            allow the truck to operate at a lower than designed ride height. A driver/owner should never
                            modify the ride height control system in any way for any reason. To do so can lead to
                            non-warrantable transmission failures.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>Suspension air spring height should be verified as part of routine maintenance at engine
                            oil change intervals. This will ensure the drivetrain system is performing as designed.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </randlist>
